    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but it still feels like the math is working against me. it feels like there's this huge chunk of my money just disappearing into the interest every month before it even touches the actual loan balance. is there a specific formula i can use to see exactly how much of my payment is going to interest vs principal each month?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely. You can use a loan amortization calculator to see how your payment is split between interest and principal each month. The general formula to calculate the interest for a loan period is: Interest = Principal * Monthly Interest Rate. The Actual Monthly Payment you are making can then be broken down as: Payment - Interest = Principal Reduction. Plug in your loan balance and interest rate at the beginning of the period to get the exact amounts being allocated. Tools like these are typically available online where you can input your loan details.",
      "source": "target",
