    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. it just feels so sneaky though. even when i pay extra towards the principal, the interest amount barely seems to budge for a long time. it's like there's something hidden in the math that keeps the interest high even when i'm trying to pay it down. is there any other factor that could be causing that kind of drag?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The principal reduction doesn't accelerate like as much as you'd hope because most student loans have front-loaded interest, meaning a larger portion of each payment goes to interests early in the loan term. This practice makes sense from a lender's perspective as it ensures they receive more predictable returns from your initial investments. There are no hidden factors, but it's just the way the interest calculations are structured. To counteract this, if you can afford to, consider making biweekly payments instead of monthly, as this can slightly reduce the interest over the loan term. Always get in touch with your lender for specific advice tailored to your situation.",
